            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Aiyana Fong is a living archive, a product of two distinct histories converging in San Francisco. Born in the city\u2019s Inner Richmond district, she is the daughter of a Din\u00e9 (Navajo) mother who moved to the Bay Area for college and a second-generation Chinese-American father whose family ran a small grocery store. Her childhood was a tapestry of traditions: celebrating Lunar New Year with her father\u2019s family and spending summers on the Navajo Nation in Arizona, absorbing her mother\u2019s stories and language. This dual heritage instilled in her a profound understanding of how easily stories can be lost if they are not actively preserved.\n\nHer path was set after her mother\u2019s death when Aiyana was in her early twenties. The grief-stricken task of sorting through her mother\u2019s photographs, letters, and recorded oral histories of elders crystalized her calling. She enrolled at San Jos\u00e9 State University, earning a Master of Library and Information Science. Aiyana began her career in the physical archives of a local museum, but she foresaw the digital shift. She championed early digitization projects, becoming a vital bridge between traditional preservation and emerging technology. Today, as the Head of Digital Archives at a major university library, she manages vast collections, ensuring that the digital footprints of communities are as carefully curated as physical artifacts.\n\nAiyana lives in a quiet, rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Sunset, a place she\u2019s called home for over two decades. Her daily routine is a comforting ritual: a walk to a local cafe for coffee, followed by the N Judah Muni line downtown. The 4.8-mile commute is her quiet time for reading. Though single, her life is rich with connection through a close-knit circle of colleagues and a book club that has met for fifteen years.\n\nHer connection to San Francisco is one of both inheritance and stewardship. She walks streets that hold her father\u2019s history and works to protect the legacies of people like her mother. Aiyana\u2019s ultimate aspiration is to launch a collaborative project: a public digital archive of Bay Area oral histories from Asian American and Indigenous communities. For her, it\u2019s not just a career goal, but a way to honor her own story and ensure the city\u2019s memory remains as diverse as its people."
